<section label="di-method">
	<title>Solutions by Direct Integration</title>

	<p>
		In the previous section, we saw how finding the antiderivative of <m>x^2</m> can be rephrased as solving the differential equation
		<me>
			y'(x) = x^2.
		</me>
	</p>

	<aside>
		<title>Link to Algebra</title>
		<p>
			Just as taking the square root of both sides of the equation
			<me>x^2 = 9</me>
			helps isolate <m>x</m>, integrating both sides of
			<me>y' = x^2</me>
			helps isolate the unknown function, <m>y</m>.
		</p>	
	</aside>

	<p>
		To find <m>y</m>, we would like a way to <q>remove</q> the derivative from <m>y'</m>. The fundamental theorem of calculus tells us that this is possible by integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.
	</p>

	<paragraphs>
		<title>Solving <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = f(x)</m></title>

		<p>
			Let's use integration to solve the following equation:
			<me>
				2y' - 4\sin x = 2
			</me>.
		</p>

		<p>
			We begin by isolating <m>y'</m>:
			<me>
				2y' = 2 + 4\sin x \quad \Rightarrow \quad y' = \frac12(2 + 4\sin x) \quad \Rightarrow \quad y' = 1 + 2\sin x
			</me>.
		</p>

		<p>
			Now we integrate both sides with respect to <m>x</m> to leave us with <m>y</m>:
			<md>
				<mrow> \int y'\ dx	\amp = \int (1 + 2\sin x)\ dx </mrow>
				<mrow> 			y + c_1	\amp = x - 2 \cos x + c_2 </mrow>
				<mrow> 						y	\amp = x - 2 \cos x + \boxed{c_2 - c_1}\leftarrow c </mrow>
				<mrow> 				y(x)	\amp  = x - 2 \cos x + c </mrow>.
			</md>
		</p>
		
		<p>
			The constants of integration are combined into a single constant <m>c</m>. This merging constants like this is standard way to simplify the solution.
		</p>

	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs>
		<title>Solving <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}[g(x,y)] = f(x)</m></title>

		<p>
			Let's extend this idea to solve the equation:
			<me>
				x^2\frac{d}{dx}\left[5x \cdot y\right] - 1 = 0
			</me>.
		</p>

		<p>
			Currently, <m>y</m> is trapped inside a derivative, but perhaps integration could release it. Start by isolating this derivative:
			<me>
				\frac{d}{dx}\left[5x \cdot y\right] = \frac{1}{x^2}.
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			To <q>remove</q> this derivative, we must integrate with respect to <m>x</m>:
			<md>
				<mrow> \int \frac{d}{dx}\left[5x \cdot y\right]\ dx \amp = \int x^{-2}\ dx </mrow>
				<mrow> 5x \cdot y + c_1 \amp = -x^{-1} + c_2</mrow>
			</md>
		</p>

		<p>
			With <m>y</m> now free, we can isolate it to obtain the solution:
			<md>
				<mrow>  5x y	\amp = -\frac{1}{x} + c_2 - c_1 </mrow>
				<mrow>  		y	\amp = \frac{1}{5x}\left(-\frac{1}{x} + c\right) \quad \leftarrow \ \text{general solution}</mrow>
			</md>
			where <m>c = c_2-c_1</m> is the combined arbitrary constant.
		</p>

	</paragraphs>

	<assemblage xml:id="direct-integration">
		<title>Direct Integration</title>
		<p>
			If a differential equation can be expressed in one of the forms:
			<men xml:id="direct-integration-equation">
				\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \quad\text{or}\quad \frac{d}{dx}\left[g(x,y)\right] = f(x)
			</men>,
			then the general solution can be found by
			<ol marker="(1)">
				<li>integrating both sides with respect to <m>x</m>, and</li>
				<li>solving for <m>y</m>.</li>
			</ol>
		</p>
	</assemblage>

	<example xml:id="direct-integration-example-2">

		<statement>
			<p>
				Find the general solution to the differential equation
				<me>
					\frac{1}{\cos x}\frac{d}{dx}\Big[y\sin(2x)\Big] - 1 = \sec x
				</me>
			</p>
		</statement>

		<solution>
			<p>
				First, we get the derivative by itself on the left-hand side
				<aside><title>☝️ Recall the Identity</title>
					<p>
						<me>
							\sec x = \frac{1}{\cos x}
						</me>
					</p>
				</aside>
				<md>
					<mrow>
						\frac{d}{dx}\Big[ y \sin(2x) \Big] \amp = \cos x\left( 1 + \frac{1}{\cos x} \right)
					</mrow>
					<mrow>
						\frac{d}{dx}
						\Big[
							\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{g(x,y)}}{\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{\uparrow}}{\ul{y\sin(2x)}}}
						\Big]
						\amp = \us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{f(x)}}{\us{\textcolor{BurntOrange}{\uparrow}}{\ul{\cos x + 1}}}
					</mrow>
				</md>
			</p>

			<p>
				Now, we integrate by sides with respect to <m>x</m>, releasing <m>y</m> from the derivative and allowing us to isolate the general solution.
				<md>
					<mrow>
						\int \frac{d}{dx}\Big[y\sin(2x)\Big]dx \amp = \int \left(\cos x + 1\right) \ dx
					</mrow>
					<mrow>
						y\sin(2x) + c_1 \amp = \sin x + x + c_2
					</mrow>
					<mrow>
						y	\amp = \frac{\sin x + x + c}{\sin(2x)}\qquad (c = c_2 - c_1)
					</mrow>
				</md>.
			</p>
		</solution>

	</example>

	<example xml:id="direct-integration-example-3">

		<statement>
			<p>
				Show why direct integration doesn't apply to the equation: 
				<me>
					\frac{dy}{dx} - y = x
				</me>
			</p>
		</statement>

		<solution>
			<p>
				Isolating the derivative gives:
				<me>
					\frac{dy}{dx} = x + y.
				</me>
				Since the derivative is with respect to <m>x</m>, we must integrate both sides with respect to <m>x</m> as well:
				<md>
					<mrow>\int\frac{dy}{dx}\ dx	\amp = \int (x + y)\ dx</mrow>
					<mrow>										y	\amp = \int x\ dx + \int y\ dx</mrow>
					<mrow>										y	\amp = \frac12 x^2 + \int y\ dx \quad \leftarrow\text{stuck}</mrow>
				</md>.
			</p>

			<p>
				The integral left behind cannot be computed because we are integrating with respect to <m>x</m>, not <m>y</m>. 
				We know that <m>y</m> is a function of <m>x</m>, but we don't know which one (if we did then we would already have the solution!) 
			</p>
		</solution>

	</example>

	<p>
		Direct integration is a simple way of solving differential equations, provided the structure allows it. If your equation can be written as
		<me>
			\frac{d}{dx}[x\ \text{and}\ y\ \text{terms}] = \text{only}\ x\ \text{terms}
		</me>,
		you're in business. Just integrate both sides and solve for <m>y</m>.
	</p>

	<exercise label="c3-2-cyu-1">
			
		<task label="c3-2-cyu-1-chkpt-1">
			<title>How could you Find <m>y</m>?</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					How could you solve for <m>y</m> in the equation
					<me>
						\frac12\frac{dy}{dx} - \tan(2x) = x
					</me>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p>Isolate <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> &amp; integrate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Correct!</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>Differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect, differentiating both sides only puts another derivative on <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>Isolate <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> &amp; integrate both sides with respect to <m>y</m>.</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect, the integration is not with respect to <m>y</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>Find the antiderivative of <m>\tan(2x)</m>.</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect, the solution is the antiderivative of <m>2\tan(2x) + 2x</m>, not just <m>\tan(2x)</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="c3-2-cyu-1-chkpt-2">
			<title>Solution ⇄ Antiderivative</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The solution to the differential equation
					<me>
						\frac13 y'- 7x + x^2 = 1
					</me>
					is the integral of which function?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\quad y</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect. <m>y</m> is the solution to the differential equation.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\quad 21x - 3x^2 + 1</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect, perhaps check your algebra.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p><m>\quad 7x - x^2 - 1</m></p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect, perhaps check your algebra.</p></feedback>
				</choice>

				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p><m>\quad 21x - 3x^2 + 3</m></p></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! Isolating <m>y'</m> gives
							<me>
								y' = 21x - 3x^2 + 3
							</me>,
							so the solution is <m>\int (21x - 3x^2 + 3)\ dx</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>

			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="c3-2-cyu-1-chkpt-3">
			<title>Does Direct Integration Apply?</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Direct integration could be used to solve the equation
					<me>
						\frac{d}{dx}\left[y^2 + x^3\right] = \sqrt{x}
					</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p>True</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Correct!</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>False</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect. This equation is in the form <xref ref="direct-integration-equation"/>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="c3-2-cyu-1-chkpt-4">
			<title>Why Doesn't Direct Integration Apply Here?</title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Give the reason direct integration cannot be applied to the equation
					<me>
						\frac{d}{dx}\left[\frac{x}{y^2}\right] = \sin(x+y)
					</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice>
					<statement><p>There is a fraction in the derivative.</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect, direct integration doesn't care about fractions.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>The <m>y</m> term is squared.</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect, direct integration can handle this.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>There is a sine term on the right side of the equation.</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect, the sine is not the issue here.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p>The right-hand side contains <m>y</m>.</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Correct! Direct integration only works when the right-hand side contains only the independent variable, in this case <m>x</m>.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="c3-2-cyu-1-chkpt-5">
			<title>Combining Constants</title>
			<statement><p>Combining constants is a common practice in differential equations.</p></statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><p> True</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Correct! Combining constants is an easy way to simplify a solution and is a standard practice in differential equations.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><p>False</p></statement>
					<feedback><p>Incorrect, revisit the examples above.</p></feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

	</exercise>

</section>